08326nam a22009735i 9780812297119DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122971197 a10.9783/97808122971192doi  a(DE-B1597)563168  a(OCoLC)1156139980  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aKZ3410b.L36 2020 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a34122300aLandscapes of Law :bPracticing Sovereignty in Transnational Terrain /ced. by Christina L. Davis, Carol J. Greenhouse. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b1 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction. Mapping Culture onto Transnational Law -- tChapter 1. A Journey Through Law’s Landscapes: Close Encounters of the Scalar Kind -- tChapter 2. Intersecting Legal Spaces: International Trade Law and Anticorruption Law -- tChapter 3. Changing Internally to Engage Externally: China and the WTO Legal System -- tChapter 4. The “Africa Bar” of Paris: A Microcosm of Interconnected Histories of Legal Globalization -- tChapter 5. Cultural Difference as Legal Resolution: The Raising of the Ehime Maru -- tChapter 6. Landscapes of Law in War- Torn Societies -- tChapter 7. Uncertain Sovereignties: Indigenous- State Relations in Colombia -- tChapter 8. Between Sovereignty and Transnationalism: The European Union as an Incomplete “Transnational Legal Space” -- tChapter 9. The Emergence of Digital Communities: Generating Trust, Managing Conflicts, and Regulating Globality . . . Digitality -- tChapter 10. Landscapes of Actually Existing Liberalism: Some Thoughts on the Historical Dialectic of Liberty and Philanthropy -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInternational scholars offer ethnographic analyses of the relations between transnationalism, law, and cultureThe recent surge of right-wing populism in Europe and the United States is widely perceived as evidence of ongoing challenges to the policies and institutions of globalization. But as editors Carol J. Greenhouse and Christina L. Davis observe in their introduction to Landscapes of Law, the appeal to national culture is not restricted to the ethno-nationalisms of the developing world outside of industrial democracies nor to insurgent groups within them. The essays they have collected in this volume reveal how claims of national culture emerge in the pursuit of transnationalism and, under some circumstances, become embedded within international law. The premise that there is inherent tension between nationalism and globalism is misleading. Whether asserted explicitly as state sovereignty or implicitly as cultural community, claims of national culture mediate how governments assert their interests and values when engaging with transnational law. Landscapes of Law demonstrates how nationalism operates in the contested zone between borderless capital and bordered states.Drawing from the fields of anthropology, international relations, law, political science, and sociology, the book's international contributors examine the ways in which claims of national differences are produced within transnational institutions. Insights from case studies across a wide range of topics reveal how such claims may be worked into policy prescriptions and legal arrangements or provide ad hoc bargaining chips. Together, they show that expressions of national culture outside of state boundaries consolidate claims of sovereignty. The contributors offer innovative frameworks for analyzing the relationships among transnationalism, law, and cultural claims at various levels and scales. They demonstrate how overlapping communities use law to define borders and shape relationships among actors rather than to generate a single social ordering.Landscapes of Law traces the theoretical implications generated by an understanding of transnational law that challenges the conventional separation of individual, community, society, national, and international spaces.Contributors: Katayoun Alidadi, Tugba Basaran, Rachel Brewster, Sandra Brunnegger, Christina L. Davis, Sara Dezalay, Marie-Claire Foblets, Henry Gao, Carol J. Greenhouse, David Leheny, Mark Fathi Massoud, Teresa Rodríguez-de-las-Heras Ballell, Gregory Shaffer, Mariana Valverde.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aInternational law. 0aNationalism. 0aSovereignty. 0aTransnationalism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aFolklore.  aLinguistics.1 aAlidadi, Katayoun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBasaran, Tugba, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrewster, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrunnegger, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Christina L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Christina L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDezalay, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFathi Massoud, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoblets, Marie-Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGao, Henry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenhouse, Carol J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenhouse, Carol J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLeheny, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRodríguez-de-las-Heras Ballell, Teres